    value: 임금의 행차가 멈춘 곳을 말한다.
english:
  title: Record of the Moon Wave Pavilion
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Five leagues east of Seonzhou lies a ferry called Yeoja, where the waters of the Nakdong flowing south from Sangju converge. It is here that travelers passing from Sangju southward must make their crossing—truly a crucial waypoint. To the east of this ferry, a small mountain rises, facing the river. When Yi Mun-jeong of Jeonju served as magistrate, he first raised a pavilion here, naming it Moon Wave. Yet the years consumed it, and it fell to ruin.

    In the spring of the first year of Jianwen, the Lord Min, now called the Prince-in-Law of Yeheung, passed through on an official mission. Grieved to find it so long abandoned with no one to restore it, he departed. Later, when Ch'oe Kwan of Daenung took office as magistrate of this county, the Prince commanded its reconstruction, and Ch'oe gladly complied. Within months of his arrival, he reformed the administration and won the people's hearts. He chose a new site north of the old foundation, upon a stone cliff, its situation more open and its beauty more striking. Wishing not to burden the people, he enlisted monks for the work. In the eighth month they began; by the tenth month it was complete. The master carpenter was none other than the chief builder of the new palace in the capital, so the structure achieved remarkable elegance and craft. He even added a heated chamber for weary travelers.

    Three years later, in autumn, Ch'oe was summoned to serve as Inspector of Waters and departed for court. The Prince of Yeheung, escorting a sacred relic, journeyed to Sungsan, and would pass this way again. He asked me to write a record for its dedication.

    I inquired of Ch'oe about the pavilion's setting. He spoke thus: "Above and below the pavilion, young pines stand thick and verdant; stone cliffs rise sheer and solemn. The long river wraps around it like a ribbon, while vast meadows extend beyond. Villages nestle upon the earth, their hearth-smoke visible to one another—such is Seonzhou. Farmers and herders, fishermen and woodcutters exchange their songs; the hunched figures moving through the fields are Seonzhou's people.

    "To the southwest the heavens seem torn asunder, and earth and water stretch boundless. Clouds and mist shift through ten thousand forms. When the river runs clear and the moon shines bright, reflections of man and shadow merge into a stillness like jade sinking into depths, yet move like gold leaping alive. Viewed from the side, they stream forth like white silk; viewed straight, they rest like a reclining tower. The whole sky and water fuse in one luminescence—this is why it bears the name Moon Wave, and this is the true marvel of this pavilion.

    "Northward stands a mountain, dense and azure, where in ancient days the progenitor of the Koryŏ kingdom halted his campaign against Silla. Its noble spirit still commands reverence, flowing eternal like the mountain streams—those who ascend this pavilion cannot but dream of those distant ages.

    "And now the Prince, bearing the dignity of his rank and the honor of his station, has come here twice, ascending to contemplate and compose verse, seeking to dwell in refined and lofty sentiments. What fortune does this pavilion not enjoy?"

    Hearing these words, I take brush to write this record.

    Written on a day in the tenth month of winter, in the year Sinsa.
  footnotes:
    - '駐蹕 (chu-pi): The resting place where an imperial procession halts. Here it refers to where the Koryŏ founder Wang Kŏn paused during his military campaigns to unify the peninsula.'
    - The Prince of Yeheung (여흥공) served as both father-in-law to the king and prime minister, making him one of the highest-ranking officials in the realm.
